Financial Position 6

This is the amount of adjusted deposits placed with the reporting party as at the relevant date.
If the total deposits placed with the reporting party exceed the amount of total deposits the reporting party has placed with others, then this amount is the total deposits the reporting party has placed with others (i.e. deposit assets).
If the reverse is true (i.e. the total deposits placed with the reporting party does not exceed the amount of total deposits the reporting party has placed with others) then the amount is the total deposits placed with the reporting party (i.e. deposit liabilities).
Liabilities Deposits ARF210 Adjusted Amount

This is the amount by which the value of Deposit Liabilities exceeds the net value of Deposit Assets. If the Deposit Liabilities do not exceed the Deposit Assets then report zero.
Deposit Liabilities are deposits held by the reporting party as at the relevant date, and which are capable of being redeemed or withdrawn by depositors from the reporting party within 2 business days, with or without penalty.
Deposit Assets are the deposits at the relevant date redeemable or withdrawable by the reporting party on demand or within 2 business days. The net value is determined by reducing the deposit amount by any break costs or early withdrawal penalties that would be applied for redeeming the deposit within 2 business days.
Liabilities Deposits ARF210 Excess Amount
This is the value of deposits at the relevant date redeemable or withdrawable by the reporting party's depositors on demand or within 2 business days.
Liabilities Deposits At Call 2 Days Amount

This is the balance of deposit accounts held by the reporting party as at the relevant date, and for which the reporting party has issued a cheque book.
Deposits are amounts which are redeemable or withdrawable by depositors from the reporting party. The value of this item is to be determined in accordance with accounting standards.
Liabilities Deposits Cheque Amount

This is the value of deposits held by the reporting party as at the relevant date, and which are redeemable or withdrawable by depositors from the reporting party, plus negotiable bearer debt securities classified as certificates of deposit.

This is the value of all deposits other than demand deposits. Demand deposits are those withdrawable or redeemable within 24 hours. This item is to be determined in accordance with accounting standards.

This is the balance of non-interest bearing deposits held by the reporting party as at the relevant date which are redeemable or withdrawable by depositors from the reporting party, and which are not classified as certificates of deposit.
Certificates of Deposit are negotiable bearer debt securities. They are certificates issued that indicate a specified sum of money has been deposited at the issuing depository institution. A certificate of deposit bears a maturity date and a specified interest rate. Their term to maturity vary in size, and may normally be redeemed before maturity only by sale on the secondary market, but may also be redeemed through payment of a penalty.
Liabilities Deposits Non Interest Bearing Amount

Deposits are amounts which are redeemable or withdrawable by depositors from the reporting party.
Term deposits refer to an account in which money has been placed for a fixed period of time for a stated interest rate.

At call or on demand deposits are deposits redeemable or withdrawable by depositors from the reporting party on demand or within 24 hours.

Certificates of deposit are negotiable bearer debt securities. They are certificates issued that indicate a specified sum of money has been deposited at the issuing depository institution. A certificate of deposit bears a maturity date and a specified interest rate. Their term to maturity vary in size, and may normally be redeemed before maturity only by sale on the secondary market, but may also be redeemed through payment of a penalty.

This is the value of the reporting party's acceptances as at the relevant date. Acceptances comprise undertakings by the reporting party to pay bills of exchange drawn on customers. These bills of exchange are not held as part of the reporting party's asset portfolio.
Acceptances are accounted for and disclosed as a liability with a corresponding contra asset. The contra asset is recognised to reflect the reporting party's claim against each drawer of the bills of exchange. The measurement and classification basis used is to be in accordance with the accounting standards.

This is the value, as at the relevant date, of all other borrowings of the reporting party, as required to be reported on APRA form SRF_110_0.
The total of: * Securities sold under agreements to repurchase, representing the payable due to counterparties with whom the stock has been lent and from whom cash has been lodged. These transactions are to be recorded consistently with AASB 139. Where the transferee of the stock effectively receives a lenders rate of return (i.e. the underlying risks and rewards of ownership of the underlying stock is not effectively transferred), these transactions are to be accounted for as collateralised lending activities (treating stock lending as on balance sheet exposures). Under this method of accounting the banks physical stock positions recorded on the balance sheet in either Trading Securities or Investment Securities sections is not affected. * Commercial paper or promissory notes - short-term debt securities issued with a residual term to maturity of 12 months or less. * Short term loans. A loan is considered to be short term if its residual term to maturity is of 12 months or less. * All other debt securities issued with a residual term to maturity of 12 months or less.

This is the value, as at the relevant date, of liabilities other than those classified as outstanding claims liability; unearned premium liability; borrowings; loan capital and hybrid securities; as determined in accordance with accounting standards.
Unearned premium income is that portion of the written premium applicable to the unused part of the period for which the premium has been paid. Thus, in the case of an annual premium, at the end of the first month of the premium period, eleven-twelfths of the premium is unearned.
Premiums, as defined by the Australian Accounting Standards, are amounts charged in relation to accepting risk from the insured, but does not include amounts collected on behalf of third parties.
Borrowings are generally amounts of money on loan from financial institutions or other creditors with the promise or understanding that it will be repaid.
For the purposes of this item, include hybrid securities classified as debt securities, loan capital, and certificates of deposit.
